There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that standard and not try it too hard, because it will end up hurting itself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics in it: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantic state"; a "state" which consists, in a large way, of some of its characteristics.
Physicians classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Article Adventure of Berkeley Laboratories, which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the months, which we will not talk about here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosnes, I might stress here, are not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge speeds up or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" is born an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of yours "power bearers".
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is about another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it you need to reach extremely high energies, a little as if it were a frozen pond in which only a thick rock could slide through the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the CERN (the big Hadron Collider is a 27 km circumference ring!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between Higgs and the mass.
