Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual coins such as "credit", used to advance in a video game and that can be won by playing or can be purchased (and even sometimes swap).
The Facebook social network also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and treats the changes.
With the bitcoin, all network nodes are both depositories of accounting books, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoins changes consist of the public account book, which is spread across the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This passes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the privilege to add that complementary line.
This is a phase of file slices, i.e. a transformation of a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical footprint.
Computers "cogen" the new transaction and add a number before "trocear" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zero at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, in order to commit a fraud, one user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would accept only one of the two transactions as valid; the other would stay orphaned, as both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the 100th millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the calculus power.
The life of the network already has its heights.
The websites that offer Bitcoin services have been attacked and bitcoins stolen in storage.
"The fault used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash presents the same defect.
Weight actors like Wikipedia reject this kind of payments.
Others, like the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the accounting book and showed that about 80% of Bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the "giant discounts" were launched.
"30,000 dollars have been changed," rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on that coin, believes quite in the potential of this technology in addition to in the network of transactions.
Your system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a mobile payment without contact, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to run in the shops, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
They just need to provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who assures he has thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
"It will take a while for Bitcoin to push, but in 2013 there could be a change," he predicts.
On the other hand, in its report, the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, if this currency succeeds.
