A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever as regards the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And nearly two years ago, Egypt used an interim text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial bottlenecks.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delusion" and continues to "treason his word" and "pisote the law".
By their supporters, it is ensured that it is a measure to speed up the institutional and political crisis and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be organized in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time requiring the Brothers to renounce their draft explanation of the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way of recovering a popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy causes damage throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or vote on my text or I maintain the full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in this strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist largely, voted the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
In mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt that they could not enforce their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 persons, substitute members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As I had hoped, the articles voted were unanimously adopted.
The commentators are also grateful that one of the few discrepancies of the day was practically expressed at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent's watch was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, subject to all looks, is finally identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that “the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law”.
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the rules", which would have allowed stricter application.
For Islamists, this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals view it as hypocritical and consider it nothing more than an artifact of advertising.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular to anyone who has to confirm its compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are further increased by the fact that the next director of that university would be much less moderate than the present one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of civil status.
Most of the lawyers who have worked in this text are not Ulemas but university students, some of them formed in the French system," Alexis Blouet explains, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But it recognizes that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, since the terms used imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to rule over all of this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms concerning the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers will claim that they are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Civil prosecutions in military courts, as requested by human rights associations, will also not be prohibited.
They also expressed concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her view, the only positive step has been the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president had to go out last night on television, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of State protested on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are expected by the Holy Land, the World's Obligatory and a Sea of Salmura
The Promised Land combines the majesty of Bible truths with modern comfort and a pristine nature.
"AIF" identified the five most important reasons why one should visit Israel.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptismal pillar" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of the miracles of Jesus: the conversion of water into wine at the wedding, walking on the waters, the calming of the storm and the nets filled.
In this very place, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places is in Jerusalem.
The believers walk here through the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Way of Pain").
It begins in the Fortaleza de Antonio, the Pretorio, where the trial took place, and continues along the streets of the Old City, goes to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of crucifixion, the Stone of the anointing and the place of burial of Jesus.
In this same place there is also the symbolic Christian ombudsman of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built in the place where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for the Jews, the Wall of Lamentations; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave notes here with their desires, which will then come true.
Perform a vertical journey
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were left of a secret refuge against the enemies, which Herod the Great commanded to build in 25 B.C. for his family.
They are located in the mountain cliffs at a height of 450 m above sea level.
And getting there by their own means, they can only those who devote themselves to climbing.
Others can reach this historic summit in the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous Hermón ski resort, where in the winter months there is a great influx of tourists.
Up to there, from the foot of the hill bus services are offered.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods were supposed to dwell on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
In this country there are about 300 museums.
On a single trip you won't be able to visit all of them.
But it is worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It preserves the ancient Manuscripts of the Dead Sea or Qumran Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the desert of Judaea, and about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Art Museum in Tel Aviv.
In his painting exhibition he has paintings of Impressionists and Expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha bathroom museum, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Cesarea it is worth passing through the exclusive private museum Ralli, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tourist guides or souvenir shops there.
Entry is free, and categorically no donations are accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars shine.
And they ring the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they bathe even in the winter months, as the water temperature does not drop from 21 degrees and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there they bathe all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is at the lowest point on the planet: 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily sustain even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People arrive here to pass treatment courses with salt water, salmon and curative clays and to strengthen their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to order their broken nerves.
Touching the mysteries of antiquity
They are preserved by the ancient part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
She passed through the famous maritime route that united Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is where Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this very place, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll through the narrow streets bearing the names of the Zodiac signs.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of your "mesmo" symbol, fortune will be in your favor.
In Jaffa you can find newly married couples who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to photograph.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the principal city of Judea and the residence of the Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The theater, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera shows.
Tourists Remember
If you travel to Israel, don't worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30 per cent of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to take it in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily changed to shekels (currently $1-3,8 shekels).
Urban transport consists mainly of buses, but in Jerusalem there is a quick tram and in Haifa is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Low City with the High City.
Actually, it's from an underground funicular.
Traveling in any type of public transport costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transhipment for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday night to Saturday sunset, markets and shops close and public transport interrupts their work.
But Sunday morning begins a new work week.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
There you will find a wide selection of dishes based on beef and lamb, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a wide variety of sauces, the falafel, which are balls of ground chick, fruits and vegetables.
