The Federal Court of Auditors (BHR) can only control federal money, which we call state funds here.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As far as local legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to draw up a comparison without specific data. However, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be specified exactly in what is best.
Could it be better, for example, with regard to the quality of inspectors?
That's for sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like making these kind of comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries that we are modeling must face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, it wouldn't be of any benefit to collaborate with our office, would it?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean for your Office? Is it in any way apparent its impact?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been demonstrated in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex post controls, a certain delay is needed.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new tool for "non-economic risk detection", whereby we have passed almost 14,000 public procurements, which have been analysed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of selection process are rectified and similar.
Do you consider the adoption of this law to be beneficial or rather a blunder for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation is "hardened" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already under the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each law not respected in the matter of public procurement meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it then make sense to harden the law this way?
I don't think so.
The system should exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We'll see where this path leads us.
The Prime Minister recently stated that the SDG would not disturb entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system forbidden or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the performance of the Office that has an obligation to carry out such controls and require obligations.
He can say, "We change the law and allow it," but he cannot say that we will do as if nothing.
In the Public Procurement Act, the regulation is fairly strict as to how formal action should be taken, and that is how it should be to protect public competition.
On the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate should be excluded with the best offer not to meet the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. That is, in my opinion, what we lack.
