Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second member country of ESA of the former bloc of Eastern Europe, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during subsequent years participated in the Agency's project commission.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began much earlier.
The Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before the Second World War, although their work was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the conference by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw astronomical observatory in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the assistants indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie Award and André Louis Hirsch for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known all over the world, and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was put on one of the craters of the moon's hidden face.
Already in 1925 a Dresina was built in Poland that was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was going to be used for the beginning of the dresin or for its braking.
The information on this Dresin is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustavem Mokrzyckiegim.
Based on the preserved material, it is evident that the investigation came to the stage of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was discontinued.
In 1937 the prototype of a photo-hunting missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna and rakietobomba lotnicza" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Comitét Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all draft missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautica (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, reference is made for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, Prof. M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) had aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Astronomical Federation.
He served this position until his death in 1959.
From 1956 onwards, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM probe rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and launched for the first time on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had a height of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed, and in the summer of 1959, the two-stage RM-2 rockets were air-tested in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was about four feet [1.4 m] tall and weighed about ten pounds [11.5 kg].
Another type of developing rocket was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor of the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the available space for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km high.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version was built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the research of the cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
The suspension of the social work law is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court suspended the social labour law.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
Of course it will be interesting to look at the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
This means, therefore, that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in constant conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of major differences in labour costs (wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to do so "causes a decline" of the competitor's price in order to make itself with most of the market and thus increase its profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most entrepreneurs, to move production abroad, to buy there cheaper or to disappear. The result is a high unemployment in those countries where the price of labour, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and thus is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social spending of the state necessarily increases.
All this gives rise to the total disinterest of employers in paying taxes and compensate for the economic and social damage they have caused in order to obtain benefits.
The situation is so universally known that there is no need to present specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the Governments of those countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, Governments make private capital available to their own population without taking into account the social decline.
This is particularly evident in the changes in existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the private capital decree, especially in terms of wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted right of employees to labour rights.
The result is a growing poverty along with an increase in the gap between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, food delivery points have existed in Germany for poor people who cannot keep up with their own work.
The number of people who receive this kind of help is now up to the million.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly common case: people employed with such a low wage that the state must pay the rest to get to the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind was made public concerning the situation of auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament.
The measures of saving virtually all the states in the south of the EU lead, without doubt, to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline of their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to mallive with a bad wage within the limit of society, with the hope that someday they will reach the private investor capital country.
Is it necessary to ask yourself where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty goes from one country to another or never comes, as Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian or African continue to work for a small part of a European wage.
This also affects all Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim to the extent of satiety that the state should not bring capital to the economy, which leads the economy to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by getting into control.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence the political march with its selfishness and hence throughout the state.
In this case, the answer is clearly yes.
The test is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, in mutual favours, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, are responsible for drafting bills to private legal enterprises, which are often linked to industry.
This type of bill is later passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
In this way, all power emanates not from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups representing their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation are rapidly in a situation such as the one described by Appianmos in his work The crisis of the Roman republic in the days of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state took time to disintegrate and the administrations occupied themselves with force."
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained illegitimately and aid to finance stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption spread without hindrance, and people came to the polls with the pre-fabricated vote"... "there were no people of a character who aspired to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls"... "He began to speak seriously that the only remedy for such a grave situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man"... Although Appianos thought of Pompeya, Caesar went up to power and transformed democracy forever into an autocracy.
The conclusion, in the same way as in antiquity, is that the present society is based on unconsidered preferences of the individual benefit without taking account of the common interests.
Private capital is not, in its essence, able to understand and claim the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as that of then, a decadence of the unprecedented elite, without an effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal-type democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
The really demoralizing fact is that the present elite completely ignores the losses of hundreds of thousands of lives, social and humanitarian catastrophes we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and recent history.
The suspension of the Public Procurement Act is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the Czech government will be forced to continue to seek other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution goes through concrete socio-political reforms, which reinforce both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
