"Market Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a world-renowned brand and Polo Ralph Lauren too.
But what is Armani Polo?
After this name it hides a name officially registered in China but which has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the true eponyms do not lodge a claim.
And even then it's not clear that they're going to be right.
"It is increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China," says Thomas Pattloch, lawyer at Taylor Wessing, who specializes in violations of protection rights in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
The copyists simply add a couple of letters to be able to record their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada is registered Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to the manufacturer of sports goods Puma.
Pattloch opens an archiver in which he keeps seats in Beijing's brand office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company requested to register the brand Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in the matter of copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are large stores of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of forgeries.
However, Pattloch's cases are of a different kind. On the basis of his clients' responsibility, he combats the fact that the trade mark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
which refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty
"It's harmful to the business, you have to fight it," Pattloch says.
"The brand makes water, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage the image suffers is enormous."
The financial losses and procedural costs of the sectors concerned are millionaires, especially in the case of luxury emblematic products.
According to data from CLSA market analysis company, with a volume of €15 billion per year China is, in size, the third luxury goods market and the one growing at the highest rate.
However, achieving the cancellation of suspicious legality registrations in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
Processes can be extended for up to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch speaks of cases in which the court dismissed a claim because it had been so long since the name that was the subject of the claim had already become a "market reality".
"If the complainant is in bad luck, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarizer because the process has damaged his brand in China," Pattloch says.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a fight against the manufacturer of Sany construction machinery, the company that was recently absorbed by the German manufacturer of concrete pumps Putzmeister.
That's why today Chinese can continue to use a very similar emblem to Mercedes's star.
Volvo's buyer, Geely, initially used a blank and blue logo that reminded BMW to a large extent; the matter was settled in the courts and Geely had to modify it.
The Lacoste clothing manufacturer lost in China against copyists from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing recognizes that in 2010 they have had difficulties due to the shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, "the work emergency situation returned to normal."
In this way, the number of unprocessed claims has been reduced by 22 per cent.
Nearly 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain outstanding.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As is usually the case in China, the figures are surprising.
Last year CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost one third more than in 2010.
This would be a new record and means that China will lead the list of new registrations around the world for the tenth consecutive year, as noted by the brand office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, which totals 5.5 million.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been set up for rights.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family company Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the group has been fighting a Chinese copycat in court.
While the Germans have been able to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the copymaker has succeeded in securing the Chinese rights on the Freudenberg brand.
"We ourselves have provoked this situation because in Germany the surnames are not protected," says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO Trademark Office also dismissed the use of the Muniches.
In the following two instances Freudenberg has been right, but the opposite side continues to fight at present.
You have to be very careful.
The case has now reached the doors of the High Court of Justice, where there is still a resolution.
Wentzler trusts that he can resolve the issue favourably and commends the professionalism of the courts.
However, it also states that "the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time."
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business archive has had to review files up to a hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposite party a "sum of six digits in euros" with the aim of reaching a friendly agreement, but was unsuccessful.
"This shows how much we care," says Wentzler.
The dangers in the Far East threaten even to affect Europe,
In particular, if copy makers are guaranteed rights on unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group has long abandoned this business area, however it has been able to prevent registration.
"You have to be very careful," Wentzler says.
Both he and counsel Pattloch recommend to German companies that they be extremely prudent when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international brand rights legislation, but what needs to be done is to "register in China also all that may be likely to be protected", as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the subject can be much more expensive than a mere record.
In fact, in case Freudenberg lost the last assault of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license rights on his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or in the segment in question would expel us from the market.
