Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial ETS include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common viral STDs are AIDS, human papilloma virus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Cracks and sarcasm are among the ETS transmitted by parasites.
What are the main groups of affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are more often given in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute is based on the basis that at least four out of five cases of syphilis registered in Germany have their origin in sexual contact with men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, tricomonas, human papilloma virus, candidiasis (hongo) and gonorrhea infections.
HIV infection among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, approximately 20 per cent of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between 15 and 25 years of age.
In our country, the human papilloma virus is also added to the most common diseases among young people.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory declaration.
According to Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has continued to decline since 2007.
In 2011, approximately 2,700 cases were recorded.
