The forms show no complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about certain issues and that the officers who visited him had spoken of these problems and had indicated to him that they would be addressed, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'without incident' (after having talked about the problems) but this does not necessarily mean that I would not have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not denounced the treatment he was receiving during the meeting in January 2011 with a board to examine the suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention at that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the “injury prevention” regime under which he was present.
