Manning said he always had a light from outside pointing to his eyes while he was asleep.
He said that if the janitors couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal claim in January 2011 on the treatment that Manning was receiving.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in the Thursday declaration that, after being forced one night to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning account to stand naked in front of the janitors and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order he had given him that he should drop the blanket he could have covered with, but recognized that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that they had forced him to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning stated that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his hems to self-injury but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night they had removed their underwear, shawls and glasses from their cells.
Their lawyers are hoping that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he has experienced during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted on the war council, which is expected to begin early next year.
The defence stated that it plans to have Manning find fault with minor crimes and defend other charges considered to be too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention are justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was held in accordance with the rules of application to any detained person in maximum custody in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawfully causing the publication of information on the Internet, leaking of national defence information and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
