For four euros, Indonesian volcano carriers play life and health carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through steep stone trails
There are people for whom their work is a hell and another who literally works in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by drawing sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, you have to go down every day to the bottom of your crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth solidifies by getting in touch with the air.
After removing large sulphur rocks, which in total come in spite of about 70 kilos, they carry them into two bamboo baskets that carry on their shoulders through steep stone trails.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the extensive carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb by step from tortoise, keeping the balance and carefully measuring their steps not to slip and fall through the cliff.
They know that any transplant could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who was exposed years ago for the risks of Kawah Ijen.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents of euro for every kilo of sulphur they extract
Once up, steps are opened between tourists who photograph them as circus monkeys and, tiresomely carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little below, at 1,850 meters high.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating since 1960 the volcano and never better said to its workers, who pay 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) for each kilo of sulphur.
Then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents of euro) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is generalized in everyday life and is used to manufacture cerillas, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As normal is to load 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," Anto explains, who usually performs three daily ports.
It takes three hours each and ends soft, but allows you to add 138,000 rupees (11,5 euros) at the end of the day.
Though it seems a misery for such inhuman effort, it is the triple of what would gain in the field.
"The mining newspaper is very high here, where the coffee collection is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) the day and the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros) ", the carrier, who previously worked as a harvester on the touristic island of Bali, clarifies.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the slum was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a people close to the volcano, for a reason of weight that, in Indonesia, is as strong as sulfur: "I married a young Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Then he has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes get irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing the skin in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to bill him despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases that fire the volcano.
It's the price you have to pay to get your dream.
"I will work two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in a more than acceptable English.
Punished for life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, a waiter or a hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing an unclean wooden cabin with other carriers, it rises every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the shadows, then down to the crater immersing himself with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
Some 400 carriers carry sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its small profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs or supply any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and to both weight.
In fact, it does not even come part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) of charge per camera that, next to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this nature park charge tourists who go to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for animals and not for people," said Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been in Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
Capable of raising up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working "everything he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, aged 18-10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulphur burns the throat and picks the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and catches the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious diseases... beyond, of course, of their usual respiratory problems, arthrosis, knee pain and sores on the shoulders, which have been distorted by the weight of the baskets.
By rocking the basket on its back, Unainik can only load 50 kilos at his 53 years of age.
Every day, he and his companions pull 15 tons of sulphur into the volcano, which three trucks move to the Tamasari warehouse, 18 kilometers away along a path of goats between the marshes.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," says Unainik opening his mouth well, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the elder, 30 years old, also works by charging sulphur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest trades in the world: the one who makes the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
Singapore looks for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame the career, stress and cost of property and education for not having children.
"The population of Singapore needs to grow."
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, we fulfill our civic duty and we believe in life!
It may seem overwhelming that these verses are part of an announcement of mint pills, but despite that - or perhaps because of that - the video became viral on YouTube in Singapore early this year.
The phrases are part of a rap using local references such as "Let's put a bao (ball) in the oven" to laugh at Singapore's birth rate.
The advertising company that made the video, BBH, welcomes the hope that with the ad they manage to draw attention to the problem in a fun way.
His creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to "his national duty."
This is pure internet, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It's the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world to reproduce ourselves, so we feel that this was a subject we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as throwing perfumes with pheromones or organizing fast dating (speed-dating).
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So let's think, why don't we do as creative as possible to solve this problem, which is to compose a rap?
1.2 children
The one who does not take it so lightly is the government of Singapore.
Spends US$1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for marriage and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all of this has had little effect.
Singapore is a city rich and high-tech state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, according to its national population division, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 - known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why do Singaporeans have no more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policies of the National Population Division, says it is due to "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities".
"That has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond getting married and forming a family," he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in singleness and delay in marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
In the meantime, an immigration policy aims to dramatically increase immigration to address the decline in the population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where xenophobia is so widespread that it is hardly disguised against many new immigrants, particularly Chinese, who are criticized for maintaining low wages and not integrating themselves.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year the Singapore government party experienced its worst election result since independence.
Since the elections, there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in birth rate has known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore's example is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe box", which can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have been very successful in sales.
However, there is concern that they can promote a life-style of singleness and discourage the developers who want to build large, family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the real estate company EL Developers, says his "shoe boxes" are sold much faster than the largest units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units run out of days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, it admits that the new rules provide clearer guidance for developers, who were previously blocked if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a state city.
While these new rules can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, speaking to Singaporeans working in the financial district of the centre would seem to have little effect.
"People are very stressed, houses are expensive, and so is education, so many people are postponing it," says a young executive.
Other people may have children.
"But it's important for me to have my own money and time," says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women mention their career, the stress and cost of property and education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, no matter how much the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans are the ones who have the last word.
