Completes the Unasur Summit without publicizing the Lima Declaration
The 6th Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven assistant representatives.
EE tried repeatedly to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources of Foreign Affairs and Presidency indicated at the beginning that they would deliver it after the closure, but then stated that it would be published at some point on the website of the Peruvian Government.
Upon being consulted by the text, they noted that the content had been presented by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information at the Summit was restricted at all times.
During the day only the soundless video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room with the message "private session, restricted audio".
The little information circulated among the reporters was delivered by the press speakers of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not Peruvian.
The only document released during the day was the list of assistant presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media asking for more data.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is Humala's pronunciation, not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the Third Summit of the Arab South American Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being persistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration which they had previously announced was also not disseminated.
On the ASPA official website, it can be confirmed that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international appointments, the Peruvian authorities endeavoured to ensure that there were secured transmission systems for all journalists but restricted information to the fullest extent.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a judgement of the Hague Court that settled a border dispute between both countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins Monday in The Hague to hear the allegations of both parties, in the process that Lima filed against Santiago.
"We will take and execute the sentence that defines the differences we are bringing to this international court today," Humala said, together with his Chilean pair.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international tribunals," added Piñera, and greeted Humala, alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they would be submitted to the ICJ occurred after Colombia had denounced this week the Bogotá Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the judgements of that international court, after a decision on maritime limits with Nicaragua which it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held with the inconsistency of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after the afternoon of Lima.
The representative read the outcome document in which he reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and the lines of action for 31 projects between South American countries were set for a total of $17 billion in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of UNASUR will give "significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship for what we are expanding the residence agreements."
He reported that actions are being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, low-price internet access across all corners of South America, and to jointly and efficiently address the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (from Latin America) must not have a triumphant matrix but must serve to expand our productive matrix and glimpse a better future for our peoples," Humala added.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of South America's spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by joining our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian president in a read message.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located on the transversal axes of his territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
The outcome document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve to reintegrate the Union of South American Nations," which is currently excluded from.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and good relations between neighbours, was another of the issues underlined by the summit.
In this regard, Colombia's president, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional appointment he hoped to meet with his partner from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat the maritime dispute respectfully after a decision of the ICJ, questioned by Bogotá.
